# Purpose

The v1.1 analysis confirmed that 94.7% of inpatient facial nerve repair
cases in NIS 2023 were coded to the wrong ICD-10-PCS section, and that
14 cases each carried S04.5 (traumatic facial nerve injury) or S01.4/S01.8
(facial laceration) diagnoses. Those counts were per-category and did not
deduplicate — a single patient may carry both codes.

This v1.2 analysis produces a **precise, deduplicated traumatic case count**
by flagging each of the 57 cases as traumatic if it carries **any** of:

- `S04.5xxx` — Injury of facial nerve (any encounter type)
- `S01.4xxx` — Open wound, cheek and temporomandibular area
- `S01.8xxx` — Open wound, other parts of head
- `V01–Y99`  — External cause of morbidity (mechanism of injury codes)

A case is classified traumatic if it meets **any one** of these criteria in
any of the 40 diagnosis fields. Cases meeting none are classified
non-traumatic. The external-cause code sweep is the most sensitive net —
it catches traumatic cases where the nerve injury code may not have been
coded specifically but where an injury mechanism was documented.

